		<div class="post" id="post-3828469">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,3828469)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-3828469">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tygently" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2038009); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2038009&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182126" alt="TyGently" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2038009)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tygently" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2038009); return false;" >TyGently</a></span> <span class="odate time_1528437680 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Jun 2018 06:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3828469">
									

<p>This is not the easiest read. I don't think it was a good idea to confront the reader with well over a thousand words of legalese right at the outset of the tale, especially when it doesn't contain anything that isn't stated in a few sentences elsewhere. You've mentioned in this thread that some people skipped it and ended up fine, but there's no indication that it's something that could or should be skipped, and that's poor story structure.</p>
<p>It kind of devalues the other collapsibles a bit, too. It's the only collapsible that doesn't add very much, but it's also the first, so it sets up an expectation that other collapsibles might be superfluous or they might confront you with a wall of text, which isn't at all how the rest of the tale goes. It's not a good first impression.</p>
<p>The rest of the story had some compelling elements, but I can't say anything felt particularly captivating. The Lethe scenario is played down enough that it doesn't register a lot of tension, nor does the lawsuit angle, which is again fairly oblique to the main thrust of the narrative. And that main thrust isn't exceptionally strong; I'm not given much of a reason to care about what's going on with Trauss, or the site experiencing financial issues, or the ramifications of the Foundation using mind-control. I'm not really sold on anything contained in the tale, and it lacks a satisfying arc for most of its narrative threads.</p>
<p>Side note, not really a critique: I find it really weird when anyone in-universe comments that the Foundation shouldn't be using anomalous things to aid in containment when literally the most distinctive and vital tool they have is an anomalous drug.</p>

							</div>

								
					
